Toggle navigation En français Browse Job Listings FAQ Contact Register Log in Log in Forgot password? DIRECTOR, Finance &amp; Facility Services London , ON Description London Public Library strengthens people and neighbourhoods by creating connections that enrich lives, inspire discovery, foster creativity, and expand possibilities. Join us as our new: DIRECTOR, FINANCE &amp; FACILITY SERVICES This is a Permanent Full-Time position Department: Financial Services Reports to: CEO &amp; Chief Librarian Classification: Management, Full-Time PURPOSE OF THE ROLE Reporting to the CEO &amp; Chief Librarian (CEO) and a member of the Library’s Executive leadership team, the Director, Finance &amp; Facility Services (DFFS) is accountable for the strategic planning, development and delivery of Finance services, which includes operating and capital budgeting process, and overseeing all aspects of the Library facilities. The DFFS leads and/or facilitates the following primary functions in collaboration with the CEO and other members of the Executive Team:Resource and business performance planning; Financial and systems accounting; budgeting, financial reporting, banking, audit relations, and any financial risk management services and facility management. The DFFS establishes and maintains internal controls to ensure compliance with financial legislation and authorities, professional standards, City of London by-laws, policies and procedures where applicable, and Library policies and procedures. The DFFS models leadership behaviours and actions consistent with the Library’s Purpose, Values and Strategic Plan. KEY ACCOUNTABILITIES: Leadership &amp; Administration Works with the CEO and Executive Team in support of the Library’s Strategic Plan. Provides financial advice and input to strategic initiatives and projects, ensuring that the Library’s financial interests are safeguarded.Regularly provides input and occasional direct reporting of pertinent information requiring financial expertise to the Library Board and Finance Committee.Ensures that staff and the Library Board have the financial and facilities knowledge and information required to meet their responsibilities. May be asked to Act as Chief Executive Officer in absence of the CEO or, as delegated, in all responsibilities.In collaboration with the CEO and other Senior Team members, leads the planning, consolidation and coordination of the annual operating and capital budgets.Leads preparation of presentations to the Library Board, City staff, and City Council, ensuring alignment with the Library’s strategic plan, compliance with Library policy, and budget directives issued by City Council and City staff Supports the CEO in the role of Treasurer to the Library Board. Prepares financial reports and monitors revenues and expenditures against budget, ensuring that expenses are controlled; advises appropriate Director of any variances and ensures that negative variances are addressed. Monitors financial aspects of leases for tenants in Library spaces and facilitates negotiation of all leases. Ensures the timely and accurate recording and reporting of financial information and preparation of financial statements. Analyzes the monthly, quarterly and annual financial statements. Prepares financial reports for the City of London, Province of Ontario and other funders. Provides City of London with quarterly budget monitoring reports. Coordinates the annual audit with external auditors. Prepares year end schedules, lead sheets, working papers and consolidated financial statements. Manages any risk requirements as may be identified in an audit management letter. Reviews and approves the annual Charity Return for Canada Revenue Agency prior to its submission. In their role as DFFS, acts as a signing officer on behalf of the Library. Reviews financial data on a regular basis for accuracy, completeness and compliance with legislation. Develops, implements, and monitors accounting controls and practices to ensure compliance with applicable legislation, standards and policies. Establishes, evaluates and monitors system-wide cost and risk control procedures and compliance to those procedures in order to mitigate financial exposure and risks. Ensures that procurement policies, methods and contracts with suppliers of goods and services provide for the effective control of expenditures. Acts as a resource for and, as required, participates in goods and services procurement. Participates in the evaluation and negotiation of contracts with external suppliers, when required. Identifies risks and inefficiencies and works with management to develop and implement mitigation solutions. Oversees cash flow forecasting, planning and management, responding appropriately where necessary in order to meet financial obligations. Performs financial analysis and financial modeling in order to provide financial and management decision-making information. Plans, organizes and directs the long-range goals and daily operations of Finance staff by managing the work and overseeing the quality and standard of work performed by direct reports.Monitors reserves and other funds, including that collected as a result of development charges, held by City and budgets accordingly to meet current and future needs; provides projections to City staff Seeks ways to continuously improve and streamline processes, procedures, systems, services and software. Administers and oversees all aspects of facilities management, building construction and major renovation projects.Oversees facility staff, ensuring performance management and safe operations.Develops and completes project business plans and communication plans in consultation with members of the Executive Team. Leads in-house planning, design and technical teams and/or represents the Library on such teams involving architects and other consultants, City of London, and other project partners, contractors, etc. Administers procurement of goods and services through Request for Proposals and other processes, ensuring compliance with the Library’s Procurement Policy.Authorizes contracted expenditure.Administers and enforces project contract requirements and oversee the successful management of key construction administrative processes.Monitors capital expenditures, prepares continuity schedules for each project, tracks project balances, prepares and submits requests for reimbursement to City of London per schedule or as required.Leads the development and maintenance of the Library’s Asset Management Plan and Facilities Master Plan. Ensures compliance with government (federal, provincial and municipal) legislation and standards. Keeps current with, and implements, associated policies and procedures to ensure compliance. Ensures compliance with the Public Sector Accounting Board (PSAB). Reviews financial data on a regular basis for accuracy, completeness and compliance with Generally Accepted Accounting Principles (GAAP) and Library policies. Collaborates and proactively works with external partners, including audit, legal, banking, technical support, City of London staff, government agencies and other suppliers, as required. Collaboratively works with City of London staff and managers (Financial Planning and Policy, Finance, Taxation etc.) regarding budget planning and presentation, quarterly monitoring reports, capital expenditures, taxation, and year-end financial reporting. Facilitates communication of all departmental information between Finance and Facility Services Department and key internal/external stakeholders.Participates Library cross-functional project teams to lend skills, competence and financial knowledge.Directs workflow of the Finance and Facility Services Department to achieve the most effective utilization of staff resources. Creates a team environment, which fosters high performance and effective working relationships. Acts as a change agent to positively encourage others and manage change. Builds support for the Library’s Strategic Plan and departmental goals/objectives by communicating expectations and measuring outcomes. Looks for daily opportunities to highlight the connection between overall strategy and day-to-day operational activities.Supervises and trains direct reports while continually looking for opportunities to improve and maximize the efficiency and effectiveness of the Department. Manages and supports staff performance and development by:Providing consistent communication, feedback, coaching and empowerment;Working with staff to address/resolve performance issues; Documenting performance and conducting performance appraisals for direct reports. Creating development plans to build core competencies and personal effectiveness.Working in collaboration with the Administrator, Training &amp; Development to ensure that there is a training model in place for the department and that staff participate in trainingPromotes staff health and safety. Participates in joint union-management committees as assigned by CEO. Participates as a team member in collective bargaining negotiations, providing financial costing and analysis. Keeps current on the provisions and interpretations of Library Board policy and the Collective Agreement and ensures that they are properly applied. Performs the duties required of a supervisor under the Occupational Health and Safety Act and Regulations. Keeps current in the field of public sector accounting and its application to the public library setting.Keeps current in the field of facilities management and its application to the public library setting. Keeps current with changes in legislation as it affects the library’s finances and facilities, and ensures the implementation of those changes. Performs other related duties as assigned.A university degree in Business Administration, Finance, Accounting or related discipline.Successful achievement of a Chartered Professional Accountant (CPA) designation and be a member in good standing.Project Management certification would be considered an asset.Eight (8) years of progressive accounting and financial management experience, preferably in a public library or public sector environment, with at least 5 years in a Senior leadership role.Proven knowledge of budgeting and financial planning. A solid understanding of financial and regulatory reporting requirements. Ensures compliance with Generally Accepted Accounting Principles (GAAP) as well as accounting standards issued by the Posting #11416 Public Sector Accounting Board (PSAB), Canada Revenue Agency regulatory requirements related to charities, GST and source deductions.Demonstrated knowledge of facilities management, asset management planning, and capital project managementDemonstrated leadership experience with proven managerial skills and excellent people skills including management, negotiation and coaching.Demonstrated knowledge of automating financial services functions and the tools required.Experience in a unionized environment is preferred. Budget Development, Monitoring and Reporting Financial Controls and Risk Management Financial Management Facilities Administration Legislation and Standards Internal and External Partners Team Leadership Human Resources Management In Collaboration with the Director, Human Resources, hires, promotes, transfers disciplines, demotes and discharges staff. Participates in interview process and provides recommendations on probationary period for direct and indirect reports.Participates in the grievance procedure for direct and indirect reports, as needed.Oversees and provides final approval on all Finance and Facility Services team members requests for vacation, overtime and leave of absences. Other QUALIFICATIONS: Education: Experience: Key Competencies: Knowledge, Skills, and Abilities: Behavioural Demonstrated level of professionalism and confidentiality with strong ethics. Demonstrated ability to work collaboratively in a team environment. Excellent organizational skills with demonstrated ability to prioritize, multi-task and manage projects.Demonstrated success in project management, with excellent organization skills and the ability to effectively prioritize projects and initiatives. Proven track record of implementing continuous improvement. Excellent detail orientation and analytical skills. Exceptional oral and written communication skills. Technical Advanced knowledge of accounting software. Proficient in the development, design and use of advanced spreadsheets Other Valid driver’s license. Interpersonal Relationships With Whom: Frequency Purpose and Type of Communication Financial Services Team Daily Project management, training, staffing resources; meetings, email, phone Facilities Team Daily Project management, training, staffing resources; meetings, email, phone CEO Daily Analysis, reporting, recommendations; meetings, email, phone Executive Team Weekly Analysis, reporting, recommendations, collaboration; meetings, email, phone Human Resources Weekly Recruitment/performance management for direct report; meetings, email, phone Library staff As needed Inquiries; meetings, phone, email Board Members Monthly Reporting, presentations, recommendations and policy development; meetings City of London staff Monthly Reporting, analysis; meetings, email, phone Landlords As needed Contract management, negotiations; email, phone External partners, contractors and tenants Weekly Contract and project management, negotiations; meetings, email, phone External auditors Annually Year end audit, analysis and inquiries; meetings, email, phone Government agencies (CRA, Service Canada, Statistics Canada, etc.) As needed Reporting, legislative compliance; email, phone Scope Direct Reports # of Direct Reports: 3 Titles of Direct Reports Manager, FacilitiesManager, Facilities Projects (pending)Manager, Financial Services Indirect Reports # of Indirect Reports: 18 Titles of Indirect Reports Accounts Receivable ClerkAccounts Payable and Procurement ClerkFund Development AssociateFacilities staff (15 FTE) Work Environment: Normal administrative office environment Communicate by telephone, e-mail, and in-person discussions. May on occasion be exposed to loud sounds and distracting noise levels, such as from office equipment. Frequent interruptions Physical and Mental Exertion: Physical: Alternating positions of walking, sitting and standing, with choice of position Occasionally moving and lifting of boxes/files Mental: Composing content for internal and external reports, correspondence, etc. Independent decision making. Set most of their daily tasks and goals without speaking to a superior first. Multiple demands and deadlines that need to be met. Concentration needed for complicated tasks. Listening to concerns, issues, inquiries from staff in the department, in other departments and outside the organization. Analyzing reports and accounts on a frequent basis with continuous interruptions. Dealing with risk management &amp; financial issues that could have a significant negative outcome for the organization. Working Hours: Work a standard 35-hour week. Remote work is currently not offered for this position Regular evening and/or occasional weekend work (no shift or premium paid). Ability to work evenings and weekends is expected. Expected to attend monthly Board and quarterly Finance Committee meetings Salary to commensurate with Education and Experience This is an Excluded position from the Bargaining unit. Applications for this position will be accepted by the Human Resources Department up to FRIDAY, DECEMBER 1, 2023 to: Human.Resources@lpl.ca Please visit our website at: http://www.londonpubliclibrary.ca No phone calls please. We advise that only candidates selected for an interview will be contacted. We are an equal opportunity employer. The London Public Library will provide accommodation to applicants with disabilities in its recruitment processes upon request consistent with the Ontario Human Rights Code and the AODA regulations. Compensation $110,000 - $145,000 annual salary. Salary to commensurate with Education &amp; Experience Closes: 1 December, 2023 Ldn Public Library London , ON Policies and Terms of Use · jobboard@bcla.bc.ca / BCLA PO BOX 19008, Rocky Point PO, Port Moody, BC V3H 0J1 window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
